Annotation

Load

if (!file.exists('gencode.v36.annotation.gff3.gz')) {
  download.file('ftp://ftp.ebi.ac.uk/pub/databases/gencode/Gencode_human/release_36/gencode.v36.annotation.gff3.gz', 'gencode.v36.annotation.gff3.gz')
}
g <- import.gff3('gencode.v36.annotation.gff3.gz')
tx2gene <- g[g$type == 'transcript'] %>%
  {tibble(txid = .$transcript_id, gene = .$gene_id)} %>%
  mutate_all(function(x) sub('\\..*', '', x))

Comparison

Merge

# merge by ensembl gene id
both <- fc %>% mutate(Geneid = sub('\\..*', '', Geneid)) %>% 
  merge(sm$counts, by.x = 'Geneid', by.y = 'row.names') %>%
  dplyr::rename(sm = V1, fc = count)

Unexpressed

fit <- lapply(both[c('sm', 'fc')], `==`, 0) %>%
  bind_cols() %>%
  euler()
plot(fit, quantities = T)

Expressed

both %>% 
  dplyr::filter(fc != 0 & sm != 0) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = sm, y = fc)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_x_log10() + 
  scale_y_log10() + 
  labs(x = 'Salmon', y = 'featureCounts')

Create DESeq object

mat <- as.matrix(both[,c('fc','sm')])
cdat <- data.frame(kind = colnames(mat)) %>% `rownames<-`(colnames(mat))
dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = round(mat),
                              colData = cdat,
                              design = ~kind)

Variance stabilization

Although differential expression analysis requires raw counts, transformed data generally works better for visualization, clustering, and other uses. Compare a simple log2 transformation versus the regularized log and variance stabilizing transformations.

keep <- rowSums(counts(dds)) >= 10
dds.filt <- dds[keep,]

# variance stabilizing, regularized log, and shift log transformations
lapply(c('vst', 'rlog', 'normTransform'), function(x) {
  match.fun(x)(dds.filt) %>%
    assay() %>%
    meanSdPlot(plot = F) %>%
    .$gg +
    ggtitle(x)
}) %>% wrap_plots(nrow = 1)

Dimension reduction

vsd <- vst(dds.filt)
plotPCA(vsd)

Hierarchical clustering

There are too many genes to perform hierarchical clustering quickly, so a subset of data will be looked at instead.

# how can you subset the data?
select <- assay(vsd) %>%
  apply(1, sd) %>%
  order(decreasing = TRUE) %>%
  .[1:100]
heatmap(assay(vsd)[select,], margins = c(10, 5))

Spot-check

Pick a gene, does the expression level seem different between conditions?

plotCounts(dds.filt, gene = select[1], intgroup = "condition")

Create DESeq object

Remove unnecessary columns. An example of how to generate a metadata object is indicated below. Within the metadata dataframe, create another column called condition, grouping together the parental (PA), NSD1 knockout (NSD1KO) and NSD1/2 double knockouts (NSD12DKO) samples. Use ~condition in the design parameter when creating your DESeq object.

mat <- as.matrix()
metadata <- data.frame(kind = colnames(mat)) %>% `rownames<-`(colnames(mat))
dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = ,

                              design = ~condition)
